body:
### Description

The alumacc pass maps `+` to the `$alu` cell.

Attributes may be assigned to the `+` operator in the source HDL.

Any such attributes are not passed on to the `$alu` cell. This is understandable to a degree,
as the `$alu` cell can map multiple operators to the same cell, and one would have to handle
possible attribute collision.

However, there currently is no plausible way to retrieve the attributes in question and
associate the original `$add` with its corresponding `$alu`.
Even without an actual attribute map, the code should preserve this information in some
retrievable fashion.

## Steps to reproduce the issue

Take this sample source code:
```
module demo(cout, sum, a, b, cin);
  
    input  [15:0] a, b;
    input cin;
    output cout;
    output [15:0] sum;

    assign {cout,sum} = a + (* test_attribute *) b + cin;

endmodule
```

Run it through a quick script:
```
read -sv demo.v
hierarchy -check -top demo
select -module demo
alumacc
```

## Actual behavior

```
/* Generated by Yosys 0.15+11 (git sha1 cbece4af0, gcc 9.4.0-1ubuntu1~20.04 -fPIC -Os) */

(* cells_not_processed =  1  *)
(* src = "demo.v:1.1-10.10" *)
module demo(cout, sum, a, b, cin);
  (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.51" *)
  wire [16:0] _0_;
  (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.57" *)
  wire [16:0] _1_;
  wire [16:0] _2_; 
  wire [16:0] _3_;
  (* src = "demo.v:3.19-3.20" *)
  input [15:0] a;
  wire [15:0] a;
  (* src = "demo.v:3.22-3.23" *)
  input [15:0] b;
  wire [15:0] b;
  (* src = "demo.v:4.11-4.14" *)
  input cin;
  wire cin;
  (* src = "demo.v:5.12-5.16" *)
  output cout;
  wire cout; 
  (* src = "demo.v:6.19-6.22" *)
  output [15:0] sum;
  wire [15:0] sum;
  assign _0_ = a + (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.51" *) (* test_attribute = 32'd1 *) b;
  (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.57" *)
  \$alu  #(
    .A_SIGNED(32'd0),
    .A_WIDTH(32'd16),
    .B_SIGNED(32'd0),
    .B_WIDTH(32'd16),
    .Y_WIDTH(32'd17)
  ) _5_ (
    .A(b),
    .B(a),
    .BI(1'h0),
    .CI(cin),
    .CO(_3_), 
    .X(_2_),
    .Y(_1_)
  );
  assign { cout, sum } = _1_; 
endmodule
```

## Expected behavior

One or more of these behaviors is expected:
```
  assign _0_ = a + (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.51" *) (* test_attribute = 32'd1 *) b;
  (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.57" *) (* test_attribute = 32'd1 *)
  \$alu  #(
```

```
  assign _0_ = a + (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.51" *) (* test_attribute = 32'd1 *) (* corresponds_to_alu = 1 *) b;
  (* src = "demo.v:8.25-8.57" *) (* corresponds_to_alu = 1 *)
  \$alu  #(
```

